1.	Give an example of synchronous communication in telecommunication networks.
Synchronous communication means sender and receiver communicate at the same time and stay synchronized with a clock or timing signal. 

Example; Telephone call, Video call, Real-time voice communication
Both sides send and receive data continuously and simultaneously.

2.	In a layered communication protocol, the lower layer adds information (e.g. addresses, check sums) to the data provided by the higher layer. 
Is this statement true or is it the other way round? Give a reason for your answer.
In a layered model like OSI, each layer performs a process called Encapsulation.
When data moves from a higher layer to a lower layer treats the entire higher-layer packet as ‘data’ and wraps it owns information around it.
-	Headers: Added to the front (e.g., IP addresses at the Network layer)
-	Trailers: Added to the end (e.g., Checksums at the Data Link layer to detect errors)
